		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">CueR</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">CueR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Most recently , CueR was also shown to regulate a previously uncharacterized gene cueP , which encodes a periplasmic protein that can also contribute to copper-resistance , particularly under anaerobic conditions ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20534583" target="_blank">20534583</a>]<br></li>
<li>Outten , F. W. , Outten , C. E. , Hale , J. , and O'Halloran , T. V. ( 2000 ) Transcriptional activation of an Escherichia coli copper efflux regulon by the chromosomal MerR homologue , CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12442888" target="_blank">12442888</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Gram-negative bacteria , excessive copper is primarily controlled by the cue regulon , which includes a sensor / transcriptional-regulator protein CueR ( Outten et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24100307" target="_blank">24100307</a>]<br></li>
<li>While CueR responds similarly to Au , Ag , or Cu to induce the expression of its target genes , GolS shows higher activation by Au than by Ag or Cu .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conversely , replacement of Pro113 by Ala in CueR lowered its response to Cu without affecting its activation by Au ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cu + affinities of CueR and GolS were examined by competition with BCS in Chelex-treated , N2-purged 1 M NaCl , 10 % glycerol , 10 mM HEPES pH 7.8 under anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR and GolS are transcriptional-regulators that bind Cu and activate target gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28924031" target="_blank">28924031</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression and puriÔ¨Åcation of CueR , GolS , CueP and SodCII from E. coli The cueR , golS , cueP and sodCII coding regions were ampli-Ô¨Åed from S. Typhimurium genomic DNA using primers : 5 ‚Ä≤ - GCATATGAATATTAGCGATGTGGCG-3 ‚Ä≤ and 5 ‚Ä≤ - GGATCCT CAACGTGGCTTTTGCGC-3 ‚Ä≤ for cueR ; 5 ‚Ä≤ - GCATATGAAC ATCGGTAAAGCAGC-3 ‚Ä≤ and 5 ‚Ä≤ - GGATCCGACTTACAGA CGCTTTGC-3 ‚Ä≤ for golS ; 5 ‚Ä≤ - CATATGTCGAAATCATCATGG-3 ‚Ä≤ and 5 ‚Ä≤ - GGATCCGGGCATTTTTTTAACG-3 ‚Ä≤ for cueP ; and 5 ‚Ä≤ - ACGGAGGTCATATGAAGCGATTAAGTTTAGCG-3 ‚Ä≤ and 5 ‚Ä≤ - GGAACACTGGATCCGGGTTATTTAATGACGCCGC-3 ‚Ä≤ for sodCII , ligated into pGEM-T , prior to subcloning into the NdeI/BamHI site of pET29a ( Novagen ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we demonstrate that expression of CopA in Salmonella depends on CueR , and that this transporter and the multicopper oxidase CuiD are essential for full copper tolerance under both aerobic and anaerobic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17768242" target="_blank">17768242</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR and GolS sense copper ( plus gold and silver ) and activate transcription of genes involved in copper resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueP is under the control of CueR and can also contribute to copper resistance ( Pontel and Soncini , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>DcopA/DgolT cells have increased CueP because hyper-accumulated copper activates CueR ( Pontel and Soncini , 2009 ; Osman et al. , 2010 ) , but again UP in the SodCII background this appears to make a negligible contribution to the metal content of these fractions relative to Zn-SodCII .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>In wild-type bacteria , golTS regulation by CueR is , however , thought to be prevented due to the preferential binding of GolS to the golTS promoter ( Perez Audero et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>YacK , a putative multicopper oxidase regulated by CueR ( Outten et al. , 2000 ) , and cusCFBA of E. coli are also involved in copper tolerance response ( Grass and Rensing , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12442888" target="_blank">12442888</a>]<br></li>
<li>When Cu is detected by CueR in the cytoplasm , a P1B1-type + ATPase CopA and the multicopper oxidase CueO are expressed ( Rensing et al. , 2000 ; Outten et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24100307" target="_blank">24100307</a>]<br></li>
<li>Typhimurium posseses the Cue copper-resistance system ( Fig. 2 ) consisting of the copper-sensing MerR-family transcriptional-regulator CueR ( alias SctR ) that upregulates expression of a copper-exporting P1B-type ATPase , CopA , and the periplasmic multicopper oxidase , CueO in response to copper ( Kim et al. , 2002 ; Lim et al. , 2002 ; Espariz et al. , 2007 ; Achard et al. , 2010 ; Osman et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>In both the absence and presence of copper , CueR binds to a conserved palindromic motif within the promoter regions of its target genes ( Kim et al. , 2002 ; Espariz et al. , 2007 ; Pontel and Soncini , 2009 ; P√©rez Audero et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR and GolS can bind to and activate expression from the promoters of the genes of both the Cue and Gol systems , implying some cross-recognition ( Checa et al. , 2007 ; Espariz et al. , 2007 ; P√©rez Audero et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not known whether Cu + occupancy of one or both metal binding sites is needed for CueR or GolS activation , and it is possible that this differs between the proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , A483 was monitored following titration of BCS ( 100 mM ) with Cu + in the absence or presence of 10 mM CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>Differences in - galactosidase activity values from the wild-type CueR and CueR in the presence of Cu were statistically signiÔ¨Åcant ( * , P 0.029 ; P113A A118P ** , P 0.001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>No signiÔ¨Åcant differences were observed from wild-type CueR and CueRA118P in the presence of Cu .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR does not bind to the column and is eluted in the Ô¨Çow-through , whereas GolS binds the column and is eluted in 1 M NaCl .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>This increase in expression is dependent on the presence of CueR , and hence directly attributable to copper , consistent with an increased copper load within the intracellular environment .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both CueR and GolS can therefore activate expression from the golTS promoter in response to copper ( at least in the absence of each other ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>Disruption of Cys-112 and Cys-120 prevents the ability of CueR to sense copper , silver , or gold in vivo and in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>To explore the ability of GolS and CueR to sense copper in S. Typhimurium further , their affinities for copper were examined in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , the CueRP113A sensor exhibited a metal activation pattern similar to the chimeric CueRL sensor ; that is , there was less response to Cu than that observed with wild-type CueR , but there were similar levels of Au-mediated induction metal-dependent golB induction pattern attained with GolSA113S and GolSA113H variants was similar to that of the wild-type GolS in both genetic backgrounds ( Fig. 6A and B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Replacement of the Ala113 residue by Pro , present in CueR as well as in its xenologues ( Table 1 ) , rendered a GolS mutant sensor with an increased sensitivity to Cu , without affecting the response to Au ions ( Fig. 2 and 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>To confirm that copA transcription in Salmonella is controlled directly by the transcriptional-regulator CueR , we first mapped the transcription start site of the gene by primer extension analysis , using RNA isolated from wildtype or DcueR mutant cells grown in the presence or absence of CuSO4 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17768242" target="_blank">17768242</a>]<br></li>
<li>To analyze the molecular bases that favor the activation of GolS by Au over Cu , the amino acid residues at position 113 , 116 , 117 , or 118 in the Au sensor were individually replaced for the corresponding residues present in CueR ( Fig. 2A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>The A118P replacement in the CueR mutant partially counteracted the effect of P113A the P113A mutation ( Fig. 5B ) , resulting in a sensor protein with a pattern of induction in the presence of Cu intermediate between wild-type CueR or CueRA118P and CueRL or CueRP113A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have previously demonstrated that the Au sensor GolS shows higher activation by Au than by Ag or Cu and that a chimeric protein with a replacement of the region between I109 and C120 of GolS for the same region of CueR ( GolSL ) induces the transcription of the GolS-controlled golB gene in the presence of either Au or Cu ions , achieving similar transcription levels with both metal ions , resembling the activation pattern of CueR-dependent genes ( 15 ) ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although not determined , this suggests that in the absence of CueR and CopA the intracellular level of Cu increases , reaching the detection threshold of GolS for this metal ion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">CueR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>Besides , GolS has an additional cysteine residue at position 111 , while S. Typhimurium CueR has a Ser and Escherichia coli CueR has an Ala at this position .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>These features are conserved in S. Typhimu-rium CueR and GolS implying similar metal co-ordination environments , with two identical sites per homodimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
<li>The structure of E. coli CueR ( Fig. 3A ) reveals a homodimer comprising three domains : an amino-terminal DNA-binding domain , a dimerisation helix , and a carboxyl-terminal metal-binding domain ( Changela et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>The structure of an amino-termi-nal truncated Zn-bound E. coli ZntR dimer has been resolved and is similar to that of CueR ( Fig. 3A ) , consisting of a helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain , a dimerization helix and a metal-binding domain ( Changela et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="DOM_collapse_similarity" for="dom_similarity_5">
FIG 5 Analysis of the roles of residues at positions 113 and 118 in Salmonella CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_5", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>Replacement of the FIG 5 Analysis of the roles of residues at positions 113 and 118 in Salmonella CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>These are GolSC111S , which only differs from GolS in the residue at position 111 , and GolSsL , which keeps the C111 , but has the 7 residues between C112 and C120 present in CueR ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results conÔ¨Årmed that spe-ciÔ¨Åc amino acid residues within the region from positions 109 to 120 of CueR and GolS determine the ability of these sensor proteins to respond to Cu and in consequence to discern between Au and Cu .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>To analyze the molecular bases that favor the activation of GolS by Au over Cu , the amino acid residues at position 113 , 116 , 117 , or 118 in the Au sensor were individually replaced for the corresponding residues present in CueR ( Fig. 2A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>An increased sensitivity of the GolS-regulated promoters to gold over copper in vivo , lead to the proposal that GolS is the first specific gold-sensing regulator , with metal selectivity toward gold being dependent on residues in the carboxylterminal loop , which differ between CueR and GolS ( Checa et al. , 2007 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Structural studies indicate that CueR has only two coordinating ligands , the S-atoms of the conserved C112 and C120 residues which are appropriate for the interaction with the 1 metal ion in a linear array but not to coordinate metal ions with a 2 charge , which requires higher number of ligands ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our analysis of the contribution to Cu sensitivity of each of the four nonconserved amino acids within the metal-binding loop between GolS and CueR clearly revealed the importance of the residue at position 113 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results allowed us to focus on the residues within the metal-binding loop that are not conserved between GolS and CueR ( i.e. , the residues at positions 113 , 116 , 117 , and 118 ) to search for determinants of metal selectivity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>GolS and CueR metal-binding loops differ in four out of the seven residues between C112 and C120 , the two cysteine residues responsible for the metal-binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Firstly , the bridging ligand at the amino-terminus of the dimerization domain that links to the metal-binding domain of the opposing monomer , either contacts the metal-binding loop ( Ser-77 in CueR ) or directly binds the metal ion ( Cys-79 in ZntR ) , the latter allowing for a tetrahedral coordination environment which is optimal for binding divalent metals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previously , we showed that the expression of the GolS-regu-lated golB gene is similarly induced by Au , Cu , or Ag in a mutant that codes for a GolS chimeric protein with the metal-binding loop of CueR ( from I109 to C120 and encompassing the two conserved cysteine residues directly involved in metal coordination ) , resembling the metal response of the wild-type Cu sensor ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we demonstrated the role of individual residues within the C112-to-C120 metal-binding loop in the metal-induced activation of GolS and CueR , the two MerR homologs that detect monovalent metal ions in Salmonella .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we dissect the metal-binding loop of GolS and CueR to identify the amino acid residues that direct metal discrimination .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this context , we observed a change in metal preference of the Salmonella MerR monovalent metal ion sensors just by swapping their metal-binding loop ( between C112 and C120 ) ; i.e. , GolSsL , which harbors the CueR loop region , responds to either Au ( I ) or Cu ( I ) , while CueRL , the CueR sensor with the metal-binding loop of GolS , is less responsive to Cu ions but conserves its Au induction capability ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>The dimer-interface forms the site of metal-binding and Cu ( I ) is coordinated in a linear two-coordinate geometry involving two cysteines , Cys-112 and Cys-120 from the same monomer ( as determined by structural analysis of E. coli CueR ) ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Copper Sensing by CueR and the Cue System A B a2 a1 a3 a4 Dimerization helix ( a5 ) Metal-binding loop a6 Figure 3 Representation of the CueR homodimer structure and determinants of metal specificity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thirdly , the buried S -- Cu -- S center in CueR has a net negative charge , and charge neutralization is proposed to arise from helix dipole and hydrogen bonding interactions that occur upon binding monovalent but not divalent , metal ions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 1 The metal-binding loop is responsible for metal selectivity in Salmo-nella GolS and CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23645605" target="_blank">23645605</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not known whether Cu + occupancy of one or both metal-binding sites is needed for CueR or GolS activation , and it is possible that this differs between the proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23171030" target="_blank">23171030</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
